When you want to be a different shade of brown 🤍

This look is lighter than her natural, yet still on the darker side. It’s a perfect way to add subtle contrast without feeling dramatically different.

Now, you know it’s brunette season all year round in my chair, but are any of you other stylists feeling like this is definitely  trending right now?

@wellahairusa #btconeshot2023_brunettes

The beautiful Kim’s hair is showing great progress! Since I’m color correcting fine and thin hair, I always take the gentle approach of slow and steady to maintain the integrity of the hair. Our first session we did babylights with a base color to soften the harsh previous color. This session, we colored her roots and then balayaged through the length to create ribbon like highlights and to continue to lift out any of the darker color that still exists — this resulted in a multidimensional look. Can’t wait for her next visit!

It’s all in the (grey) blend! 

Her grow out is seamless and requires minimal maintenance. I see this client about 3 times a year and her hair continues to look amazing all year round. I’ve had quite a few new clients come recently who have been seeing their stylist every 6/8 weeks and they don’t have grey! Unless you have a decent amount of grey, prefer a lighter/darker base color or you’re wanting to be a heavily highlighted blonde to the root, this maintenance is not necessary for those wanting natural lived in hair!

My goal is always to achieve very low maintenance looks with grey blending as long as tolerable until it forces you to come frequently — at this point we would discuss whether we want to begin to go even lighter to continue to blend or commit to more maintenance if staying on the dark side. 

What is grey blending? 

Grey blending consists of fine highlighting that is fairly consistent with your grey pattern with a root shadow slightly lighter than your natural. As your greys grow out and the root shadow fades, the greys appear seamless into the highlights. Having the fine highlights  disguise the existing grey, so everything looks natural and intentional. 

And for the ladies who don’t mind rolling  with the grey, more power to you for embracing it! 

Lift:
Wella Blondor + 20vol

Root:
Koleston Perfect 55/0, 55/02 + Pastel

Tone:
Color Touch 10/73, 9/0, 8/0 + 6vol

She wanted to go darker and richer than her natural, but remain low maintenance. I went one shade darker than her natural level and used demi-permanent. As her hair grows, the demi will begin to fade — allowing the growout to feel totally seamless. The biggest tip when wanting to achieve a darker look with minimal maintenance is applying the demi permanent on damp hair and allowing it to process the full amount of time. Applying a demi to dry hair may cause permanent adjustments to their natural color, which can result in a harsh line of demarcation. Occasionally, this process can require me to double process their hair, meaning tone, rinse and tone again, to get the right depth and tone I’m looking for. Another important step in this process is preparing your client for realistic expectations! The color will fade, so they will need to come in every 12 weeks to keep it as fresh as it feels when they leave. This guest in particular wanted to go darker now, allow it to fade out over winter and then go lighter for spring. This allows nice flexibility in looks without commitment. 

I’d also like to note a little disclaimer, I achieved this low commitment look using @wellahairusa and can’t guarantee your color line of choice would have the same results. If you haven’t experimented with Wella, I highly suggest giving it a shot!

Tone:
Wella Color Touch 5/3 + 6vol
